name: (1R)-endo-fenchyl alcohol
Reason: The compound (1R)-endo-fenchyl alcohol is based on the fenchane scaffold with an alcohol functional group. The basic fenchane structure is similar to that of adamantane, which has a high melting point due to its highly symmetric, compact, and densely packed structure. Adamantane has a melting point of around 270 degrees Celsius. The addition of the hydroxyl (-OH) group to fenchyl alcohol introduces the capability for hydrogen bonding, which generally increases the melting point. However, the one hydroxyl group in (1R)-endo-fenchyl alcohol is not enough to maintain the high melting point seen in adamantane due to the alcohol's capability of forming only one hydrogen bond per molecule, in contrast to multiple hydrogen bonding often found in solids with higher melting points. Furthermore, the compactness of the adamantane-like structure is somewhat disrupted by the addition of the alcohol group, which will likely decrease the melting point. Overall, there is a dramatic drop in the melting point due to the introduction of only a single hydroxyl group and the loss of some crystalline packing efficiency. The decrease in melting point due to the hydroxyl group can be roughly estimated to be around -230 degrees Celsius from the adamantane-like baseline.
